        <title>Compiling and Running Sensu Go on ARM</title>
        <link>http://localhost:1313/archive/sensu-go-on-arm/</link>
        <pubDate>Thu, 09 May 2019 19:49:32 -0500</pubDate>
        
        <guid>http://localhost:1313/archive/sensu-go-on-arm/</guid>
        <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;updates&#34;&gt;UPDATES
&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;When I originally wrote this post, I was operating under some outdated assumptions when it comes to building Sensu on arm devices. I&amp;rsquo;ll post the updates here at the beginning of the article, and you can read on to see how I&amp;rsquo;d previously set up Sensu on my Nvidia Jetson Nanos.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;compiling-sensu-go&#34;&gt;Compiling Sensu Go
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;As a Go novice, I didn&amp;rsquo;t fully understand the workflow for compiling Sensu for arm devices. As it so happens, it&amp;rsquo;s fairly easy to cross-compile from whatever device you&amp;rsquo;re on and then just transfer the binaries to the system you want to run on. I found this out the hard way by trying to compile on the Raspberry Pi&amp;rsquo;s I have. This resulted in them locking up.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So let&amp;rsquo;s walk through the non-build-script way of doing this:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Install Go&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;#obtaining-sensu-go&#34; &gt;Obtain Sensu Go&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Build the binary for your arm system of choice using &lt;code&gt;GOOS=linux GOARCH=arm go install ./...&lt;/code&gt; from inside the project root (&lt;code&gt;$GOPATH/src/github/sensu/sensu-go&lt;/code&gt;)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Transfer to the binary/binaries to your Pi&amp;rsquo;s, Nano&amp;rsquo;s, or other arm board&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Proceed through the &lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;#running-sensu-go&#34; &gt;rest of the setup&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now, you can absolutely run through the original post as it was and &lt;em&gt;still&lt;/em&gt; run Sensu. However, I find that cross compiling from a system with a bit more oomph is going to make things easier.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h1 id=&#34;original-post&#34;&gt;Original post
&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;In this post, I&amp;rsquo;ll cover how I am running Sensu Go on several NVIDIA Jetson Nanos. Though this is being done on a Nano, you could use the same approach I use here on a Raspberry Pi, or any other armv7 board. I would note that this is a temporary until official Sensu Go arm packages are released.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h1 id=&#34;the-setup&#34;&gt;The Setup
&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;There are several things you&amp;rsquo;ll need to do before you can start playing around with Sensu Go.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Install Go on your system&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Grab Sensu Go&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Build the binaries&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;installing-go&#34;&gt;Installing Go
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;While installing Go on the Jetson as fairly trivial, the goal here is to give you a complete accounting of how I did what I did.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To install Go, run:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;sudo apt-get install golang&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You should then have it installed on your system. If you need more complete documentation on installing Go, please see &lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;https://golang.org/dl/&#34;  target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;
    &gt;Go&amp;rsquo;s docs on downloading and installing Go onto your system&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;obtaining-sensu-go&#34;&gt;Obtaining Sensu Go
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Once you&amp;rsquo;ve installed Go, the next step is to obtain Sensu Go. To get the package, run the following:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;go get github.com/sensu/sensu-go/...&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This will put the package at &lt;code&gt;$GOPATH/src/github.com/sensu/sensu-go&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;building-the-binaries&#34;&gt;Building the Binaries
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Next up, we&amp;rsquo;re going to build the binaries using a script provided in the repo. You&amp;rsquo;ll want to ensure that you&amp;rsquo;re in &lt;code&gt;$GOPATH/src/github.com/sensu/sensu-go&lt;/code&gt;. Once you&amp;rsquo;re there, you&amp;rsquo;ll find a script called &lt;code&gt;build.sh&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;
&lt;table class=&#34;lntable&#34;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;2
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;3
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;4
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;5
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;6
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;7
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;8
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-fallback&#34; data-lang=&#34;fallback&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;❯❯❯❯ ls
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;agent    dashboard       rpc        vendor           Dockerfile.rhel_atomic  build.ps1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;api      docker-scripts  scripts    version          Dockerfile.testagent    build.sh
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;asset    examples        system     CHANGELOG.md     FAQ.md                  docker-compose.yaml
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;backend  graphql         testing    CONTRIBUTING.md  Gopkg.lock
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;cli      handler         transport  DCO              Gopkg.toml
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;cmd      js              types      Dockerfile       LICENSE
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;command  licenses        util       Dockerfile.rhel  README.md
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;We&amp;rsquo;ll run that and build our binaries:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;./build.sh&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now, we&amp;rsquo;ll grab that binaries that were built:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;
&lt;table class=&#34;lntable&#34;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;2
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;3
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-fallback&#34; data-lang=&#34;fallback&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;cd $GOPATH/bin
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;sudo cp sensu-{agent,backend} /usr/sbin/
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;That&amp;rsquo;s it for the prep work. Now it&amp;rsquo;s on to actually running Sensu Go.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h1 id=&#34;running-sensu-go&#34;&gt;Running Sensu Go
&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;To run Sensu Go, we&amp;rsquo;ll need to go through the following steps:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Create the service files for the respective services&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Create the Sensu user/group&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Create the respective directories needed for Sensu to operate&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Grab config files for Sensu Go&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;creating-the-service-files&#34;&gt;Creating the Service Files
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;There are two service files that will need to be created in order to use systemd to manage Sensu Go as you&amp;rsquo;d find with RHEL/Debian packages:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sensu Backend Service File&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;
&lt;table class=&#34;lntable&#34;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt; 1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt; 2
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt; 3
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt; 4
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt; 5
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt; 6
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt; 7
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt; 8
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt; 9
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;10
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;11
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;12
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;13
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;14
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;15
